@node Word jumping in line
@section Word jumping in line

@findex avy-extras-goto-word-in-line
@findex avy-extras-goto-word-in-line-behind
@findex avy-extras-goto-word-in-line-ahead
When editing prose or code, you often want to jump to a nearby word on the same line without being overwhelmed by candidates from the entire visible window. Three commands restrict @code{avy-goto-word-0} to the current visual line:

@itemize
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-word-in-line} offers candidates across the entire visual line, from its beginning to its end.
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-word-in-line-behind} offers candidates only between the beginning of the visual line and point. This is useful when you need to jump backward to fix a typo earlier on the same line.
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-word-in-line-ahead} offers candidates only between point and the end of the visual line.
@end itemize

All three commands use @code{avy-goto-word-0} internally, so they respect your @samp{avy} style and key settings.

@node End-of-line jumping
@section End-of-line jumping

@findex avy-extras-goto-end-of-line-above
@findex avy-extras-goto-end-of-line-below
Sometimes you want to append text at the end of a nearby line. These commands combine @code{avy-goto-line-above} or @code{avy-goto-line-below} with a subsequent @code{end-of-line} call:

@itemize
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-end-of-line-above} jumps to a visible line above the cursor and moves point to its end.
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-end-of-line-below} jumps to a visible line below the cursor and moves point to its end.
@end itemize

Both accept optional OFFSET and BOTTOM-UP arguments, which control the distance between the closest avy candidate and the cursor and the display order of candidates, respectively.

@node Mode-specific jumping
@section Mode-specific jumping

@findex avy-extras-dired-find-file
@findex avy-extras-ebib-view-entry
@findex avy-extras-headers-view-message
@findex avy-extras-telega-view-message
@findex avy-extras-elfeed-search-show-entry
Several Emacs modes display lists of items (files, bibliography entries, email messages, chat messages, feed entries) where you select an item by moving to its line and pressing a key. These commands combine line selection and action into a single step:

@itemize
@item
@code{avy-extras-dired-find-file} jumps to a line in a Dired buffer and visits the file or directory on that line (via @code{dired-find-alternate-file}, which reuses the current buffer).
@item
@code{avy-extras-ebib-view-entry} jumps to a line in an Ebib index buffer and opens the entry for editing (via @code{ebib-edit-entry}).
@item
@code{avy-extras-headers-view-message} jumps to a line in a mu4e headers buffer and views the message (via @code{mu4e-headers-view-message}).
@item
@code{avy-extras-telega-view-message} jumps to a line in a Telega chat list and opens the chat (via @code{push-button}).
@item
@code{avy-extras-elfeed-search-show-entry} jumps to a line in an Elfeed search buffer and displays the entry (via @code{elfeed-search-show-entry}).
@end itemize

@node Character jumping
@section Character jumping

@findex avy-extras-goto-char-forward
@findex avy-extras-goto-char-backward
These commands provide Vim-style @samp{f} and @samp{F} motions: they prompt for a character and immediately jump to its first occurrence in the specified direction. Unlike @samp{avy-goto-char}, which displays overlay hints for all visible occurrences, these commands jump directly to the nearest match and then allow you to repeat the jump by pressing the same key again.

@itemize
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-char-forward} prompts for a character and jumps forward to its first occurrence. Pressing the same character again within the timeout period (@ref{@code{avy-extras-goto-char-timeout}}) advances to the next occurrence. Pressing a different key or waiting for the timeout exits the search and processes the key normally.
@item
@code{avy-extras-goto-char-backward} works the same way but searches backward.
@end itemize

The last character used is stored in the variable @code{avy-extras-last-char}.

